text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!PracticeCategory]]%0a%0a!Speaking vs Understanding Languages%0a%0a:Author: shreya_r%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aWhy is it usually easier to learn to understand a language than it is to speak it?%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aAt least in my case, I've found that there is an enormous difference between being able to understand a different language and being able to communicate in it. There are several languages where I can understand basic conversations, mostly because I've picked them up by listening to people speak them all the time, but if asked to, I can barely speak the simplest words and phrases on my own. This also seems to be the case with non-native English speakers who can understand English well but struggle to speak it themselves. So, why is there such a big difference between understanding and speaking a language (and similarly, reading and writing in a new language) especially in terms of things like knowledge of vocabulary? %0a%0aAlso, is it usually easier to speak/understand a new language or read/write in it? I've noticed that for me it depends on the language, but I'm curious about what factors would affect that. (For example, is it related to the way you learned the language?)%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: :)